Long Sun Exposure Causes Shriveling – The More Shriveled, The Riper!
Because our dragon fruit is grown on tropical highland farms with ample sunlight, it naturally thrives under full exposure to sunlight and rain. As a result, some fruits may develop dry skin, wrinkles, scars, black spots, or water cracks. These are completely normal and do not affect the flesh inside. In fact, dragon fruit that has endured natural elements like wind, sun, and rain tends to be even sweeter and juicier.
Wrinkled Skin
Cracks, Scars
Dry Stem, Slightly Black Scales
After harvesting, the stem of the dragon fruit, like aloe or cactus, contains a lot of moisture. If not dried properly, it may mold. You can cut off the stem or ignore it and enjoy the fruit. The flesh is unaffected. If this concerns you, please do not purchase.
